WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the library of
congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:18.370 --> 00:00:19.670
&gt;&gt; Karen Lloyd: Good afternoon.

00:00:19.670 --> 00:00:21.630
What a panel of experts
we have here today?

00:00:21.630 --> 00:00:24.370
So I think everybody's
in for a real treat.

00:00:24.370 --> 00:00:27.090
I'm Karen Lloyd, Director of
the Veterans History Project

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:30.070
and it's my pleasure to welcome
you to the most beautiful building

00:00:30.070 --> 00:00:32.970
in Washington, D.C. On the wall

00:00:32.970 --> 00:00:36.430 position:56%
in the Veterans History Project
Information Center, which is located

00:00:36.430 --> 00:00:40.250
across the street in the Madison
building is a Maya Angelou quote,

00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:43.560
which perhaps you've heard
before, "There is no greater agony

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:46.780
than bearing an untold
story inside you."

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:49.310
Monday is Memorial
Day, a day I hope,

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:52.450
before everyone starts their
festivities, they take a minute

00:00:52.450 --> 00:00:55.030
to remember those who gave
their lives in service

00:00:55.030 --> 00:00:58.630
to our country, the
ultimate sacrifice.

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:01.550
We should also be mindful that
many who returned home from war

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:05.220
and military service did
not come back unscathed

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:07.700
and that's why we are
gathered here today.

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:12.760
Post-traumatic stress disorder,
PTSD, the invisible wound

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.060
that affects hundreds of veterans.

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:19.090
Over 30% of Vietnam
veterans and 10% of Iraq

00:01:19.090 --> 00:01:22.770
and Afghanistan veterans
experience PTSD.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:26.050
But it's not just the
combat vets who are at risk.

00:01:26.050 --> 00:01:31.450
Sexual assault and trauma can also
produce this debilitating disorder.

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:35.650
PTSD can impact a veteran's ability
to work, to interact with friends

00:01:35.650 --> 00:01:37.580
and family, just to live.

00:01:37.580 --> 00:01:41.510
While it's a -- while
it's a major factor

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:43.210
in veterans becoming involved --

00:01:43.210 --> 00:01:44.680
and it's also a major factor

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:48.650
with veterans becoming involved
with our justice system.

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:49.950
While we are participating

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:53.330
in the Veterans History Project
cannot cure veterans of PTSD,

00:01:53.330 --> 00:01:56.190
we hear from veterans
and experts alike

00:01:56.190 --> 00:02:00.440
that say unburdening the weight of
their story provides some relief.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:04.430 position:56%
At the Veterans History Project we
make veterans' experiences available

00:02:04.430 --> 00:02:07.360
to researchers so they
can be better understood.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:11.560
We hold events like this to let
veterans know they are not alone,

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:15.250
to raise awareness of programs such
as the Veterans Treatment Court,

00:02:15.250 --> 00:02:19.880
that positive creative
outcomes for veterans with PTSD.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:23.890
Today you are -- you will hear
plenty of ideas and experiences

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:28.180
about PTSD and Veterans
Treatment Courts,

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:31.810
but those ideas will be useless
if they stay in this room.

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:35.430 position:56%
I hope you will learn something
from this panel and take it with you

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:36.730
and use it to make a difference

00:02:36.730 --> 00:02:40.380
in someone's life,
even if in a small way.

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:43.820
June is National PTSD
Awareness Month, a perfect time

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:46.080
to get involved whether
it's volunteering

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:48.170
with a veteran's service
organization

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:50.700
or interviewing the veteran
in your life for VHP.

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:55.590
Again, we appreciate you choosing
to be here today to learn more

00:02:55.590 --> 00:03:00.210
about PTSD and how we
can support our veterans.

