00:05:54.250 --> 00:05:58.670
Um, but the battle at Combat
Outpost Keating had tipped him

00:05:58.670 --> 00:06:00.770
into a chiasm chasm of sorts.

00:06:00.770 --> 00:06:04.560
He lost two of his best friends,
Michael Scuuza and Chris Griffin,

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:08.940
um, during an attempt, uh, to
save, uh, five men who were trapped

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:10.860
in a Humvee during the battle.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:16.070
Um, he, Griffin, another guy
named Sergeant Joshua Hart, uh,

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:19.790
had tried to rescue them stuck
in a Humvee and another Humvee.

00:06:19.790 --> 00:06:22.830
At the end of the day, of the
three men in the rescue truck

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:26.720
and the five men in the
Humvee that was trapped, um,

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.180
only three of them survived.

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:30.440
Um, and Faulkner was one of them.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:35.760
And he had, as a lot of people
have, um, survivor's guilt.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:38.730
Faulkner's commander
at Fort Carson, um,

00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:41.280
had already suspected
he was self-medicating,

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:43.260
um, with illegal drugs.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.000
Um, which he thought
was contributing

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:46.770
to what he was going through.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:51.360
He decided it would be better
to discharge Faulkner, um,

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:53.880
before he got in so much
trouble that he was, um,

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:57.380
dishonorably discharged
or even court-martialed.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:03.750
Um, the decision upset Ed's
father, Ed Faulkner Sr., um,

00:07:03.750 --> 00:07:05.880
who reached out to his congressman.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.290
Um, his son needed
psychological therapy,

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:11.270
not humiliation, the dad said.

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:15.050
But the Army thought that they were
doing Ed Faulkner Jr. a favor, um,

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:18.660 position:56%
by kicking him out in a way that he
would be able to preserve his access

00:07:18.660 --> 00:07:21.230
to the VA and his benefits.

00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:28.240 position:56%
So, April 1st, 2010, Ed Faulkner Jr.
and Ed Faulkner Sr. boarded a plane,

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:31.480
um, back home to North Carolina.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:34.190
As soon as Ed Faulkner Jr. got
back to Burlington, North Carolina,

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:36.960
he retreated into his own head.

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:40.180
Um, he did keep in touch with some
of his friends through Facebook,

00:07:40.180 --> 00:07:43.850 position:56%
but he described himself as haunted.

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:47.390 position:56%
He dreamt about Iraqis coming to his
family's door, ringing the doorbell,

00:07:47.390 --> 00:07:50.140
bringing their dead babies to him.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:52.730
He lamented to his father that
he could have done something

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:57.140
to save his friend Chris Griffin's
life, but was not able to.

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:59.650
When the son was out, he
would have flashbacks.

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:03.760
When the moon was out, he was
scared awake by nightmares.

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:06.720
Michael Scuuza, his
friend, had once been able

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:09.280
to comfort Faulkner whenever he
was having a tough time saying,

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:10.580
"It's all good, man.

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:11.920
It's all good," but
Scuuza was now gone

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:14.800 position:56%
and wasn't able to say that anymore.

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:18.340
In April, 2010, Faulkner
started in a carpet cleaning job.

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:19.960 position:56%
He would get up at 6:00am every day.

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:23.530
His boss showed him how to use
the cleaning system on his van.

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:26.040
When Faulkner stepped into a
bucket of scalding hot water,

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:28.940
he said the blisters hurt
worse than his bullet wound,

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:32.570
but he was trying -- he was
trying to make a life for himself.

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:35.960 position:56%
But the outpost always never left Ed
Faulkner Jr. He would stay up late

00:08:35.960 --> 00:08:37.890
at night watching the videos

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:40.770
that the insurgents
had posted on YouTube.

00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:44.260
Uh, he told a friend from
3-61 that he heard gunfire

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:46.790
and saw Taliban every day.

00:08:46.790 --> 00:08:49.720
His father took him to a Greensboro
Grasshoppers minor league baseball

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:51.640
game on the 4th of July.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:54.630
When the fireworks started,
Faulkner hit the ground

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:56.920
as if he was under attack.

00:08:56.920 --> 00:08:59.490
Once in the middle of the night
Faulkner's mom could not find him.

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:01.310
He wasn't in his bed.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:03.210
His truck was still in
the driveway, though.

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:04.910
He didn't answer his cell phone.

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:06.210
She got in her car in
the middle of the night,

00:09:06.210 --> 00:09:07.510
drove around the neighborhood
looking for him.

00:09:07.510 --> 00:09:09.050
He wasn't anywhere.

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:11.990
When she returned, as she pulled
into the driveway, she saw a shadow

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:13.610 position:56%
in the bushes in front of the house.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:16.160
She walked over and she found
her son crouched down acting

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:19.530
as if he had a rifle and as if
he were looking through its scope

00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:21.820
as an enemy -- at an
enemy across the street.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:23.850
He picked up an invisible
radio and started talking

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:25.810
to it -- into it as if in combat.

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:27.430
She guided him to his bed.

00:09:27.430 --> 00:09:30.030
The next morning, he
remembered none of it.

00:09:30.030 --> 00:09:33.200
At the end of July 2010
Ed Faulkner Jr. ran naked

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:36.000
into the street yelling that
the end of the world was coming.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.780
He stopped cars and asked
drivers if they had been saved,

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:41.870
if they had accepted Jesus
Christ as their lord and savior.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:43.170
He was picked up by local police

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:45.450
who called his sister,
Sara Faulkner Minor.

00:09:45.450 --> 00:09:47.460
She told them that her brother
had recently been discharged

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:49.990
from the Army, had two
Purple Hearts, one from Iraq,

00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:52.030
one from Afghanistan, he
had shrapnel injuries,

00:09:52.030 --> 00:09:53.330
and he was suffering from PTSD.

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:56.760
"I knew it," said the police
officer, "When we detained him,

00:09:56.760 --> 00:10:00.270
he was talking on the radio to
fellow soldiers who weren't there."

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:03.530
Both were imaginary, of course,
the soldiers and the radio.

00:10:03.530 --> 00:10:06.960
The officer said that the police
did not want to arrest Faulkner.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:08.310
They would commit him.

00:10:08.310 --> 00:10:09.610
Sara agreed.

00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:10.930
She didn't want him to hurt
himself or anyone else.

00:10:10.930 --> 00:10:13.310
So she visited him at
the psychiatric wing

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:15.680
of Alamance Medical
Center in North Carolina.

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:19.120 position:56%
At first, she walked right past his
room because his mattress was thrown

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:21.860
to the floor, the occupant
inside was covered

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:23.910
from head to toe by a sheet.

00:10:23.910 --> 00:10:26.030
The room clearly belonged
to somebody else,

00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:28.230
not her brother, somebody unhinged.

00:10:28.230 --> 00:10:29.530
"Whoever that is, bless his heart,"

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:32.660
she said to herself
before realizing it was Ed.

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:33.960
And she walked in.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:35.260
She tried to make conversation.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:36.560
It didn't sound like
his voice when he spoke.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:38.090
Something had taken him over.

00:10:38.090 --> 00:10:39.390
He scared her.

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:42.750
He said to her, "I can't
sit in this nuthouse."

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:44.570
The realization knocked
the wind out of her.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:46.500
She said, "My brother
is very ill right now."

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:48.650
He said, "This is the end for me.

00:10:48.650 --> 00:10:49.950
You have no idea how I feel.

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:51.250
I'm so stressed out.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:52.550
I don't know why I did what I did.

00:10:52.550 --> 00:10:54.260
I don't know why it happened."

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.320
She tried to tell him to
give his life over to God,

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.710
that only God could
save him, not drugs.

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:02.970
But, to her, her brother
seemed beyond saving.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:05.920
"There's all this noise in my
mind," he told her, "It won't stop.

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:07.550
It won't quiet down."

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:10.330
Faulkner was transferred to
a local veteran's hospital

00:11:10.330 --> 00:11:11.630
for a couple of days.

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:14.090
He was assigned a social worker
and then he was discharged.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:16.220
His parents were not
impressed by the quality

00:11:16.220 --> 00:11:17.730
of care their son received.

00:11:17.730 --> 00:11:19.030
It all seemed very casual.

00:11:19.030 --> 00:11:20.330
It all seemed very oblivious.

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:23.320 position:56%
He clearly needed some serious help.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:26.280
His father would say, "If you're
out in a storm, you seek shelter.

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:28.820
Ed has a storm going
on in his brain."

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:33.050
But his government, his
country provided his son

00:11:33.050 --> 00:11:35.230
with no such shelter.

00:11:35.230 --> 00:11:39.360
Faulkner soon met a woman
named Sharleen in August.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:42.510
She told him that she was bipolar,
she suffered from manic depression.

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:45.150
For the first time in a long
time, Faulkner did not feel alone.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:46.690
He had Sharleen.

00:11:46.690 --> 00:11:48.220
She knew how he felt.

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:49.720
She had a young daughter.

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:53.860
He helped her with her homework,
a normal life, or almost.

00:11:53.860 --> 00:11:55.520
He moved into her two
bedroom apartment

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:57.180
within weeks of meeting her.

00:11:57.180 --> 00:11:58.480
She was on government assistance.

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:00.040
She lived in subsidized
housing provided

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:02.130
through the Burlington
Housing Authority.

00:12:02.130 --> 00:12:04.480
She was prescribed asserted
medications including Methadone

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:05.780
and Xanax.

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:07.440
She'd been investigated a
few times by local police

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:11.000
for selling the narcotics
that she had been prescribed.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.360
To Ed's family, all of this
seemed cause for alarm,

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:15.210
but he was unyielding,
"I don't have to live

00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:16.510
in the biggest house," he said.

00:12:16.510 --> 00:12:17.810
"I don't need life's finest.

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:19.110
So what if she's on welfare?

00:12:19.110 --> 00:12:20.410
So what if she's in
government housing?

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:23.470
These people are closest to God."

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.830
Sharleen got on the phone
one time with Ed's sister.

00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:28.290
"I love your brother,"
she told Sara.

00:12:28.290 --> 00:12:30.650
She seemed space out -- spaced out.

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:32.250
Her voice was rambling.

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:34.240
"I can tell you're on
drugs," Sara replied.

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:35.570
"Lock them up.

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:37.190
My brother was once
addicted to pain pills.

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:38.990
Keep them out of his reach."

00:12:38.990 --> 00:12:40.290
Sharleen promised that she would.

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:41.590
After all, she had a little girl.

00:12:41.590 --> 00:12:43.240
She had to keep her medications
out of her hands as well.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.960
On the night of September
15th, 2010,

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:49.220
Sharleen found Ed Faulkner
Jr. drifting off to sleep

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:51.740
in his parked truck
behind the steering wheel.

00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:53.790
When she asked him what was
wrong, he didn't answer.

00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:56.430
She helped him stumble out of
the vehicle and into her bed.

00:12:56.430 --> 00:12:57.730
The next morning, Sharleen woke up

00:12:57.730 --> 00:12:59.400
and got her daughter
ready for school.

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:00.970
She took her to the bus stop.

00:13:00.970 --> 00:13:02.550
When she came back, she
was surprised to see

00:13:02.550 --> 00:13:04.830
that Ed hadn't moved an inch.

00:13:04.830 --> 00:13:06.730
She realized he wasn't breathing.

00:13:06.730 --> 00:13:08.030
She called 9-1-1.

00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:09.330
She tried to revive him.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:12.670
The fire department
arrived, took over the CPR.

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:15.050
The first responders noticed
that there were several buckets

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:16.750
of murky water in the hallway.

00:13:16.750 --> 00:13:18.520
It wasn't clear whether the
apartment had functioning

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:20.530
electricity or plumbing.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:22.770
The mattress on which Ed
Faulkner Jr. was lying was riddled

00:13:22.770 --> 00:13:24.460
with cigarette burns.

00:13:24.460 --> 00:13:27.750
The apartment was packed with
piles of clothing and trash.

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:30.170
The bathroom was coated in filth.

00:13:30.170 --> 00:13:31.950
The police and ambulance
got there at the same time.

00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:33.580
The emergency medical
technicians ran in

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:35.630
and confirmed what the
firefighters already ascertained.

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:37.850
Ed Faulkner Jr. Was dead.

00:13:37.850 --> 00:13:39.150
They put him on a stretcher.

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:40.450
They wheeled him out.

00:13:40.450 --> 00:13:41.750
They placed in the
back of the ambulance

00:13:41.750 --> 00:13:43.050
and they sped off to
the emergency room.

00:13:43.050 --> 00:13:46.860
An autopsy indicated his cause of
death was acute methadone toxicity.

00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:50.870
A few days later, a Veterans
Administration Office worker called

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:53.940
Ed Faulkner Sr. "Would you please
let your son know he's late

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:55.240
for his appointment?"

00:13:55.240 --> 00:14:00.620
he asked. As word of Ed
Faulkner Jr.'s death spread,

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:04.250
his former sergeant, Jonathon
Hill, called Tye Carter,

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:08.790 position:56%
another fellow soldier from 3-61 Cav
to discuss how thoroughly the Army

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:13.500
and then the VA had turned
their backs on their friend.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:16.110
Tye Carter, who would later be
awarded the Medal of Honor said,

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:19.690
"I kind of think Ed was the
9th victim of COP Keating

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:22.730
and I honestly don't
think he'll be the last."

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:25.430
There needs to be a
place in American society

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:27.240
for the Ed Faulkner
Jr.'s of the world.

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:29.280
I don't have the solutions.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:30.580
I'm a reporter.

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:32.100
I'm not a policy maker.

00:14:32.100 --> 00:14:37.270
But whether it's in the Army or in
the VA or in our local communities,

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:40.080
they are not somebody
else's problem.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:44.240
They are not somebody in the street
just blocking you from getting

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:46.710
to work when you want
to get to work.

00:14:46.710 --> 00:14:49.450
They are our problem.

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:51.250
That we are not doing
enough to save men

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:55.560
like Ed Faulkner Jr.
is a national disgrace.

