00:27:17.250 --> 00:27:22.180
&gt;&gt; I was dealing with suicidal
thoughts, suicidal attempts.

00:27:22.180 --> 00:27:27.220
&gt;&gt; I got arrested for domestic
violence, uh -- uh -- two assaults.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:30.400
&gt;&gt; I ended up catching
my first case --

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:32.910
my first legal case where I was
looking at two years in prison.

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:34.210 position:56%
&gt;&gt; When I returned home from Vietnam

00:27:34.210 --> 00:27:37.860
in 1968 I had no idea what
post-traumatic stress disorder was.

00:27:37.860 --> 00:27:41.150
I just thought, hey, everything's
normal and I was drinking a lot.

00:27:41.150 --> 00:27:44.870
&gt;&gt; I got into drinking and, you
know, and the stuff that goes

00:27:44.870 --> 00:27:47.420
with that, kind of acting
out, being very reckless.

00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:48.720
I was addicted to drugs.

00:27:48.720 --> 00:27:50.030
I was drinking a lot.

00:27:50.030 --> 00:27:54.240
I was making bad decisions and, um,
basically it all caught up with me.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:55.730
&gt;&gt; My drinking picked up.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:59.600
You know? And pretty much
spiraled out of control.

00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:05.900
And my lowest point
was, uh, I was homeless.

00:28:05.900 --> 00:28:10.210
I -- I lived in my
truck for three months.

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:14.540
I got my 3rd DUI and I ended
up in Boone County Jail.

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:16.750
&gt;&gt; I tell a lot of people
the hardest part about going

00:28:16.750 --> 00:28:20.500
over there is coming back home,
reconnecting with friends,

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:22.850
everybody changed over the
course of me being gone.

00:28:22.850 --> 00:28:26.460
And, I don't know, I felt
like a stranger coming back.

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:28.370
&gt;&gt; The friends you make
in the civilian world,

00:28:28.370 --> 00:28:31.940
although they are really
great friends,

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:34.130
they're not like the friends
you have in the Marine Corps.

00:28:34.130 --> 00:28:35.930
And when you're in the
Marine Corps it's a --

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:37.830 position:56%
it's a sisterhood and a brotherhood.

00:28:37.830 --> 00:28:40.620
&gt;&gt; One of my really
good friends was killed.

00:28:40.620 --> 00:28:43.660
I mean it really devastated me.

00:28:43.660 --> 00:28:47.050
I wanted nothing to do with
anybody, but, you know,

00:28:47.050 --> 00:28:48.800
crawl into a bottle and go drink.

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:53.640
&gt;&gt; There was this young girl,
maybe about 16, 17 years old

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:56.050
and she was a catch year.

00:28:56.050 --> 00:29:00.510
And I saw her in my
mind wearing a burqa.

00:29:00.510 --> 00:29:04.320
Instantly I wanted to punch her.

00:29:04.320 --> 00:29:07.830 position:56%
And I remember shooking my shoe left
to right and I tapped on the floor

00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:12.310
and I said, "This isn't sand
and this isn't dirt and I'm not

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:14.110
in another country somewhere."

