I had four years -- about two and a
half to three years in the infantry

00:40:49.860 --> 00:40:52.780
and was lucky enough to get
involved in special forces,

00:40:52.780 --> 00:40:55.160
went to the special
forces qualification course

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:59.870 position:56%
after ranger school, and ended up at
28 years of service at the age of --

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:03.980
in 2003, at the age of 50 being
told by the reserve and guard,

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:05.280
"Well, you're too old now.

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:07.470
You didn't make full
colonel so you're out."

00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:09.640
So I kind of just went
back to being a judge,

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:12.190
which is what I was doing
for a living anyway.

00:41:12.190 --> 00:41:18.190
About 2000 -- I think it was the
fall of 2009, we started seeing,

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:23.030 position:56%
on our bench, an influx of primarily
young males, but some young females,

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:27.170
who were coming in with really no
criminal history and no background

00:41:27.170 --> 00:41:29.430
that was no more or less
like we normally saw

00:41:29.430 --> 00:41:32.160
with the quote normal
criminals coming in.

00:41:32.160 --> 00:41:35.240
The common thread for these
folks coming in with DUIs,

00:41:35.240 --> 00:41:39.980 position:56%
reckless driving, assaults, domestic
violence cases was military service.

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:41.950
And we -- I noticed that
they were all veterans.

00:41:41.950 --> 00:41:45.040
At that time I was running
a domestic violence court

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:49.940
and I researched and I checked out
and I found Judge Robert Russel

00:41:49.940 --> 00:41:51.580
and -- an incredible man.

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:54.640
And, for the most part, we
modeled everything we did

00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:57.490
after him in Spokane County.

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:00.800
With that we put together
a veteran's court.

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:04.320
Um, and after the first year, we're
getting ready to go to graduation.

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:05.790
We're going to graduation
with our first guy.

00:42:05.790 --> 00:42:07.280
We're very, very excited.

00:42:07.280 --> 00:42:11.270 position:56%
Our first guy, I won't give you his
last name, but he had served four --

00:42:11.270 --> 00:42:14.100
two tours with the
ranger battalion in Iraq.

00:42:14.100 --> 00:42:17.850
And then he did two National
Guard tours over the course

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:21.420
of this period with
the 1-61 infantry.

00:42:21.420 --> 00:42:25.270
And he was a psychology
student at WSU.

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:28.780 position:56%
Spokane Washington's about 60 north.

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:32.110
His beloved girlfriend in Spokane
called him up one day and said,

00:42:32.110 --> 00:42:33.820
"Hey, I think we're
going to break up,"

00:42:33.820 --> 00:42:36.490
and did what any good Ranger
Battalion guy would have done

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:38.760
at that time, probably drink
about a half a fifth of whiskey,

00:42:38.760 --> 00:42:40.520
hopped in his car, drove
all the way to Spokane.

00:42:40.520 --> 00:42:44.070
And as he was professing his
love gently rapping on the door

00:42:44.070 --> 00:42:48.150
to his girlfriend who was at 9-1-1,
two law enforcement officers came

00:42:48.150 --> 00:42:50.800
up behind him and he turned
a perfectly good misdemeanor

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:52.440
into three felonies.

00:42:52.440 --> 00:42:54.600
He had two assaults on an officer.

00:42:54.600 --> 00:42:58.470
He had the breaking and
entering into the apartment.

00:42:58.470 --> 00:43:03.050
And when they brought us before
him that year earlier, that time,

00:43:03.050 --> 00:43:05.080
they reduced the felonies
to misdemeanors,

00:43:05.080 --> 00:43:08.370
carried them for dismissal
if he completed this program.

00:43:08.370 --> 00:43:10.340
And he did complete the program.

00:43:10.340 --> 00:43:13.850
As a matter of fact, he requested
to get out early by about two weeks

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:17.920
