00:46:10.730 --> 00:46:15.940
So not knowing what to
do, I called my dad.

00:46:15.940 --> 00:46:19.940
And I said, "Pop, what do I do?"

00:46:19.940 --> 00:46:23.570
He said, "I don't want
you in the Army."

00:46:23.570 --> 00:46:30.420
Um, and um -- "I don't want you in
the Marines because they're already

00:46:30.420 --> 00:46:33.330
over there and they're
getting their ass kicked."

00:46:33.330 --> 00:46:36.620
Um -- so he said, "Why
don't you try the Navy?"

00:46:36.620 --> 00:46:43.070
So I, uh, found out where the local
-- the nearest Navy recruiter was

00:46:43.070 --> 00:46:45.140
and ran over there and joined.

00:46:45.140 --> 00:46:48.390
And just after I'd raised my hand,

00:46:48.390 --> 00:46:52.600
I ran into a high school
classmate in his uniform.

00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:54.810
He really looked sharp.

00:46:54.810 --> 00:46:59.540
He said, "Tom," he said, "Are
you still going to school?"

00:46:59.540 --> 00:47:00.840
I said, "Yeah.

00:47:00.840 --> 00:47:04.810
But I'm not taking enough hours
so I got drafted and here I am."

00:47:04.810 --> 00:47:06.760
He said, "What was your major?"

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.510
I said, "Premed."

00:47:08.510 --> 00:47:12.650
He said, "Well, you ought to
sign up to be a corpsman."

00:47:12.650 --> 00:47:16.550
He said, "I just did two years
at Memphis Naval Air Station.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:18.250
There was women.

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:19.700
Skills I learned.

00:47:19.700 --> 00:47:22.590
I had to wear a uniform,
but it was cool."

00:47:22.590 --> 00:47:25.600
So I ran right in and signed
up to go to corpsman school

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:29.380
and whenever -- when I got home,
I thought my father was going

00:47:29.380 --> 00:47:31.270
to beat the crap out of me.

00:47:31.270 --> 00:47:33.260
He said, "You know
what corpsman do?"

00:47:33.260 --> 00:47:34.560
I said, "No, pop."

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:38.630
He said, "They serve
with the Marines."

00:47:38.630 --> 00:47:46.310
So, um, I served with the
Marines in Vietnam off and on,

00:47:46.310 --> 00:47:49.860
3rd Mar Division, 3rd
Battalion, 3rd Recon.

00:47:49.860 --> 00:47:55.590
Um, got the magic wound in the
spring of 1968 at Khe Sanh.

00:47:55.590 --> 00:48:00.790
Um, when I came home
the country was nuts.

00:48:00.790 --> 00:48:05.090
I tried to be an EMT or
what they call EMTs now,

00:48:05.090 --> 00:48:08.530
but there was no coordination
amongst police, fire,

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:12.060
or emergency medical people.

00:48:12.060 --> 00:48:15.410
So we, um, went into a situation.

00:48:15.410 --> 00:48:16.710
I went to Roxbury.

00:48:16.710 --> 00:48:18.010
I was in Roxbury, Massachusetts.

00:48:18.010 --> 00:48:22.440
I went back to Boston for the love
of a woman, which didn't work out.

00:48:22.440 --> 00:48:27.780
Um, and got called down
to the projects for, um,

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:30.480
gunshot wound on the 7th floor.

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:35.650
Well, the elevators weren't working
and we had to, uh, take a door off

00:48:35.650 --> 00:48:43.690
and put this -- large person
on the door and take her

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:47.610
down seven floors while
people were shooting.

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:52.000
And I thought, "You just came
back from two years of this stuff.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:54.490
You didn't know why you were there.

00:48:54.490 --> 00:48:58.110
Now you're here in the
country of origin, OK,

00:48:58.110 --> 00:49:01.420
and you don't know
what's going on here."

00:49:01.420 --> 00:49:08.150 position:56%
So I fooled around a little bit
with anti-war groups, VVAW, uh, SDS,

00:49:08.150 --> 00:49:11.110
couple of other groups, and
decided the only way I could deal

00:49:11.110 --> 00:49:15.800
with things was to throw myself
into school, which I did.

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:19.790
Um, that's how I dealt
with my stuff.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:28.220 position:56%
Um, participating in what we called
rap groups, we met in the libraries,

00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:30.420 position:56%
meeting rooms, we met in churches --

00:49:30.420 --> 00:49:34.960
church basements, at bars in
the back rooms where we talked

00:49:34.960 --> 00:49:37.370
about our common experiences

00:49:37.370 --> 00:49:39.890
because there were no
vet centers at the time.

00:49:39.890 --> 00:49:44.480
And, in fact, the current vet
center system as we know it came

00:49:44.480 --> 00:49:49.740
out of vets rap groups
started by Vietnam vets.

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:54.600
In any case -- so I went -- I just
went threw myself into school and,

00:49:54.600 --> 00:49:58.190
um, got to the point I've got
more degrees than a thermometer.

00:49:58.190 --> 00:50:03.640
The point being that's how I
dealt with it and got interested

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:10.260
in veterans issues as I thought
of them via my academic work.

00:50:10.260 --> 00:50:16.530
My last academic position,
I ran a little, um, center,

00:50:16.530 --> 00:50:20.800
a research center, and we studied
high risk behaviors including

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:25.360
suicide and violence.

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:30.980
Um, so that's how I
got from there to here.

00:50:30.980 --> 00:50:39.030
I think the courts are a
phenomenal -- phenomenal happening.

00:50:39.030 --> 00:50:41.930
And the word needs to be spread.

00:50:41.930 --> 00:50:48.140
I -- as some of my colleagues have
already said via their experience,

00:50:48.140 --> 00:50:51.230
um, it's incredible.

00:50:51.230 --> 00:50:55.370
One -- one story and then I'll
-- I'll shorten things up here.

00:50:55.370 --> 00:51:01.550
Uh, as part of them, um, white
book procedures, I spent some time

00:51:01.550 --> 00:51:07.030
out on the west coast in a veterans
court out there in Santa Ana,

00:51:07.030 --> 00:51:09.490
and so Santa Ana where
the courts located,

00:51:09.490 --> 00:51:12.710
it's not in a very
nice neighborhood.

00:51:12.710 --> 00:51:15.450
In fact, when I got there
and stuff they wanted know

00:51:15.450 --> 00:51:21.180
if I wanted an escort, um,
because I'd come in at like 7:30

00:51:21.180 --> 00:51:23.170
in the morning and
not leave until 7:30

00:51:23.170 --> 00:51:25.930
in the evening doing my
interviews and stuff.

00:51:25.930 --> 00:51:31.360 position:56%
But the most impressive things about
it was that a new judge had taken

00:51:31.360 --> 00:51:37.830
over in the vet court there, uh,
and he was trying to fill the shoes

00:51:37.830 --> 00:51:41.810
of someone who had big
shoes to fill in the vet --

00:51:41.810 --> 00:51:44.430
vet court treatment business.

00:51:44.430 --> 00:51:49.110
Um, and so when I walked
into his chambers,

00:51:49.110 --> 00:51:53.130 position:56%
here were all these books written by
veterans about veterans et cetera.

00:51:53.130 --> 00:51:54.430 position:56%
I thought, "Hey, that's pretty cool.

00:51:54.430 --> 00:51:55.730
He's trying to learn.

00:51:55.730 --> 00:51:57.030
He's not a veteran."

00:51:57.030 --> 00:52:01.780
But he had surrounded himself
with veterans as part of the --

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:07.980
of the veteran treatment
court in Santa Ana.

00:52:07.980 --> 00:52:11.440
And then the most amazing
thing happened.

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:12.770
They were talking about the docket.

00:52:12.770 --> 00:52:15.260
People on the docket for the day.

00:52:15.260 --> 00:52:19.720
And the judge looked at
me and he said, "Doc,

00:52:19.720 --> 00:52:21.890
would you mind staying around.

00:52:21.890 --> 00:52:24.900
I think maybe we'd like
your professional opinion."

00:52:24.900 --> 00:52:29.370
Now, I have some degrees
in mental health.

00:52:29.370 --> 00:52:31.090
So I said, "Sure."

00:52:31.090 --> 00:52:36.300
So I did. Now this was a very,
very, very, very serious case.

00:52:36.300 --> 00:52:39.240
We are talking pyromania here.

00:52:39.240 --> 00:52:43.930
Not only the individual,
but anything around him.

00:52:43.930 --> 00:52:48.360
OK? So the person really
needed help.

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:54.570
So the discussion focused on how
can we best help this person,

00:52:54.570 --> 00:52:59.840
help this person who has this
really serious problem caused

00:52:59.840 --> 00:53:01.250
by his military service.

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:06.940
He had TBI among -- very
serious TBI amongst other things.

00:53:06.940 --> 00:53:11.840
And I think, in my --
in my humble opinion,

00:53:11.840 --> 00:53:17.250
they did the best thing they
could and that is they put him

00:53:17.250 --> 00:53:21.190
in a supervised condition,
conditions --

00:53:21.190 --> 00:53:24.260
living conditions --
where he was monitored.

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:25.960
Because if he would have
been on the outside --

00:53:25.960 --> 00:53:29.330 position:56%
he did want to live with his sister.

00:53:29.330 --> 00:53:32.060
But if he'd lived with his sister,
he'd've burned her house down

00:53:32.060 --> 00:53:36.080
and perhaps killed her
and her family as well.

00:53:36.080 --> 00:53:39.500
And I thought, "Wow.

00:53:39.500 --> 00:53:43.490
Wow." but it was thoroughly
discussed

00:53:43.490 --> 00:53:44.850
by all the members of the court.

00:53:44.850 --> 00:53:47.600
There was no acrimony involved,
"Well this guy did this.

00:53:47.600 --> 00:53:50.470
He's burned down houses
and this kind of thing and,

00:53:50.470 --> 00:53:53.240
you know, we need to lock him up."

00:53:53.240 --> 00:53:57.900
It was amazing -- an amazing,
um, event for me to --

00:53:57.900 --> 00:54:03.020
so I think the vet courts, as I
said earlier a few minutes ago,

00:54:03.020 --> 00:54:09.010
are the best thing that's happened
and I really appreciate, um --

00:54:09.010 --> 00:54:12.080
what some folks are doing now
is looking at when folks get

00:54:12.080 --> 00:54:18.160
out of the system and how we
get them back, um, into life.

00:54:18.160 --> 00:54:22.030
Because prison is a different life.

00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:26.160
Uh, but, in any case, it's the best
thing that's happened to veterans,

00:54:26.160 --> 00:54:30.410
um, since the VA was started
and we all know about the VA.

00:54:30.410 --> 00:54:34.650
But in any case, I'll turn it
over to this marine over here.

