00:56:15.900 --> 00:56:17.200
I was kind of by myself.

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:20.200
Society really wasn't ready for
the veterans that were coming back

00:56:20.200 --> 00:56:22.140
from Iraq and Afghanistan.

00:56:22.140 --> 00:56:24.540
So it was a lonely time in my life.

00:56:24.540 --> 00:56:27.030
So I just make sure that I'm there
every week for those veterans

00:56:27.030 --> 00:56:29.170
that are behind a wall today.

00:56:29.170 --> 00:56:31.620
Um, and it's been a
rewarding process.

00:56:31.620 --> 00:56:34.620
Um, I just try to continue
to do this every single day

00:56:34.620 --> 00:56:35.920
and I'm lucky to be here.

00:56:35.920 --> 00:56:38.490
I'm lucky that I have
friends at Justice for Vets.

00:56:38.490 --> 00:56:40.480
That organization, I can't
say enough about them,

00:56:40.480 --> 00:56:43.790
what they do in this country
for veterans every single day.

00:56:43.790 --> 00:56:45.090
It's absolutely amazing.

00:56:45.090 --> 00:56:46.390
So, um, that's all I got.

00:56:46.390 --> 00:56:47.690
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: All right.

00:56:47.690 --> 00:56:48.990
Good to have all of you here.

00:56:48.990 --> 00:56:52.220 position:56%
So it's important to point out, too,
if you're just new to the term PTSD

00:56:52.220 --> 00:56:54.460
or perhaps you don't really
understand how it works,

00:56:54.460 --> 00:56:57.700
if you have a common cold,
the symptoms are easy.

00:56:57.700 --> 00:56:59.000
You got fevers.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:00.300
You got chills.

00:57:00.300 --> 00:57:01.600
You stay in bed.

00:57:01.600 --> 00:57:02.900
You're weak.

00:57:02.900 --> 00:57:04.200
PTSD isn't so simple.

00:57:04.200 --> 00:57:06.060 position:56%
It doesn't have any kind of symptoms
that you necessarily can point to.

00:57:06.060 --> 00:57:08.750
In one individual it could be
severe, it could be chronic,

00:57:08.750 --> 00:57:10.300
it could be debilitating
to the point

00:57:10.300 --> 00:57:11.840
where they can't get out of bed.

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:13.480
And in another, he'll
be fully functioning

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:14.780
or she'll be fully functioning,

00:57:14.780 --> 00:57:16.610
but just in an instant
something happens.

00:57:16.610 --> 00:57:19.640
So you can't have a blanket
approach to treat PTSD.

00:57:19.640 --> 00:57:22.080
I'm sure all of you on stage
would agree with that as well.

00:57:22.080 --> 00:57:24.020
Judge, I wanted to
start with you, though.

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:26.690
You talked about it a little
bit in your introduction.

00:57:26.690 --> 00:57:29.480
In most of the cases, what
percentage would you attach?

00:57:29.480 --> 00:57:32.530
For the folks that come before
your bench who are veterans,

00:57:32.530 --> 00:57:35.810
how many would you suspect would
not be before you had they not

00:57:35.810 --> 00:57:38.360
experienced what they
did in service?

00:57:38.360 --> 00:57:40.190
&gt;&gt; Vance Peterson: I'd
say as much as 80%.

00:57:40.190 --> 00:57:44.280
Again, these folks, the
patterns that we normally see,

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:47.520
there's a progression after
somebody passes out of juvenile,

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:49.750
goes into a young adulthood.

00:57:49.750 --> 00:57:53.260
And you can see a certain number
of criminal events that may occur.

00:57:53.260 --> 00:57:54.560 position:56%
And they may be light weight things.

00:57:54.560 --> 00:57:56.480
It could be just a driving
while license suspended.

00:57:56.480 --> 00:57:59.220
It could be a series of speeding
tickets or reckless driving,

00:57:59.220 --> 00:58:01.840
maybe a minor assault of some kind.

00:58:01.840 --> 00:58:06.150
But the pattern that we saw,
it wasn't like that at all.

00:58:06.150 --> 00:58:11.160
The instances generally occurred
after their tours of duty.

00:58:11.160 --> 00:58:13.600
And so I would easily
say it's probably 80%

00:58:13.600 --> 00:58:17.240
of them wouldn't have been in front
of us but for whatever happened

00:58:17.240 --> 00:58:18.700
to them during their deployments.

00:58:18.700 --> 00:58:20.550
&gt;&gt; Jonathon Elias: And
the courts or corrections,

00:58:20.550 --> 00:58:23.200
they always had one fit --
one size fits all approach

00:58:23.200 --> 00:58:24.920
to dealing with veterans.

00:58:24.920 --> 00:58:26.220
That's changed, though?

00:58:26.220 --> 00:58:27.520
&gt;&gt; Vance Peterson: That's
changed substantially.

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:29.060
We've developed a number
of therapeutic courts.

00:58:29.060 --> 00:58:33.690
I was surprised to hear there's
3,000 some, um, mental --

00:58:33.690 --> 00:58:36.770
excuse me -- drug courts
in the nation today.

00:58:36.770 --> 00:58:39.350 position:56%
I know there's 330 veterans' courts.

00:58:39.350 --> 00:58:42.370 position:56%
And my push is that we should
probably have 3,000 veterans' courts

00:58:42.370 --> 00:58:45.150
because that's about
what we're going to need.

00:58:45.150 --> 00:58:47.040
The change, it's substantial.

00:58:47.040 --> 00:58:50.780
The veterans are given, I don't
want to say preferential treatment

00:58:50.780 --> 00:58:53.400 position:56%
because often times the probationary
requirements we put them

00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:55.810
on the veterans court is greater
than what they're going to have

00:58:55.810 --> 00:58:58.760 position:56%
