&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Right.

01:05:30.290 --> 01:05:38.120 position:56%
The story, I came back, uh, I was
in, um, St. Louis airport and I'm --

01:05:38.120 --> 01:05:40.840
I'm honored as a Navy corpsman.

01:05:40.840 --> 01:05:44.450
I wear the Marine -- I can
wear the Marine green uniform.

01:05:44.450 --> 01:05:46.930
OK? There's a special
band on the sleeve

01:05:46.930 --> 01:05:50.790 position:56%
that distinguishes me as a corpsman.

01:05:50.790 --> 01:05:56.430 position:56%
So I had my medals on and stuff, or
ribbons on, and walked up to the bar

01:05:56.430 --> 01:05:59.630
in the airport and ordered a drink.

01:05:59.630 --> 01:06:03.240
Uh, had a few anyway
on the airplane.

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:06.560
Uh, in any case, there was a guy
at the bar looks at my uniform

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:09.480
and he said, "How many
babies did you kill?"

01:06:09.480 --> 01:06:13.890
And before I could hit him
with the beer bottle, OK?

01:06:13.890 --> 01:06:17.490
The bartender grabbed this guy
and threw him out of the bar.

01:06:17.490 --> 01:06:20.150
That's my first experience
coming back.

01:06:20.150 --> 01:06:22.960
Now the guy was probably sloshed
and -- and the whole business,

01:06:22.960 --> 01:06:25.550
but that was my reaction.

01:06:25.550 --> 01:06:26.850
All right?

01:06:26.850 --> 01:06:31.000
And then not being able
to go places in uniform

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:36.820
because people would really --
let's just say really rude to you.

01:06:36.820 --> 01:06:40.280
OK? With language we didn't
even use in the Corps.

01:06:40.280 --> 01:06:45.670
OK? Um, but Tim's exactly right.

01:06:45.670 --> 01:06:49.590
When you come back,
it's so different.

01:06:49.590 --> 01:06:50.890
It's so different.

01:06:50.890 --> 01:06:55.230
And nobody knows how to
deal with you because of it.

01:06:55.230 --> 01:06:59.550
I appreciate -- I appreciate
what the country --

01:06:59.550 --> 01:07:02.220
how it values it's veterans,

01:07:02.220 --> 01:07:07.150
but they need to understand
war changes people.

01:07:07.150 --> 01:07:09.330
It changes people.

01:07:09.330 --> 01:07:14.140
And so it's not just, "Thank
you for your service."

01:07:14.140 --> 01:07:15.640
It's, "Welcome home."

01:07:15.640 --> 01:07:19.970
And there's a big difference
between those two phrases.

01:07:22.490 --> 01:07:24.790
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Your experience?

01:07:27.450 --> 01:07:32.260
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Well, two years
ago I went to the first reunion

01:07:32.260 --> 01:07:36.430
of my college fraternity
of more than 30 years.

01:07:36.430 --> 01:07:42.190
There were about 50 of us in this
really nice Italian restaurant

01:07:42.190 --> 01:07:44.720
in New York City, in Manhattan.

01:07:44.720 --> 01:07:51.970
Uh, and these are good guys,
guys I was friends with.

01:07:51.970 --> 01:07:54.010
They're lawyers.

01:07:54.010 --> 01:07:58.280
They're doctors, dentists,
college professors.

01:07:58.280 --> 01:08:03.940
And of the 50 there were four of
us who served in some capacity

01:08:03.940 --> 01:08:05.780
or other in the military.

01:08:05.780 --> 01:08:10.080
One, a lawyer friend of mine,
was in the National Guard.

01:08:10.080 --> 01:08:14.620
Another guy, he was
an 11 Bravo, a grunt,

01:08:14.620 --> 01:08:16.290 position:56%
but they didn't send him to Vietnam.

01:08:16.290 --> 01:08:18.600
They sent him to Germany.

01:08:18.600 --> 01:08:23.220
Third guy did not want to get
drafted so he thought he was smart.

01:08:23.220 --> 01:08:27.600
He joined the Air Force
and wound up in Thailand

01:08:27.600 --> 01:08:32.310
where he lost his best friend
and lost a lot of other guys.

01:08:32.310 --> 01:08:40.590
And it -- there was, to me,
a kind of barrier, in a way,

01:08:40.590 --> 01:08:44.230
between me and these other fellows.

01:08:44.230 --> 01:08:45.530
Good guys.

01:08:45.530 --> 01:08:47.680
You know? Successful guys.

01:08:47.680 --> 01:08:52.540
The people I'm most
comfortable around are veterans.

01:08:52.540 --> 01:08:58.590
Uh, and I know when I came home --

01:08:59.660 --> 01:09:05.620 position:56%
it's something that you didn't
necessarily talk about, but I was --

01:09:05.620 --> 01:09:10.700
like Doc -- I was a little bit
angry at what had been going on.

01:09:10.700 --> 01:09:12.870
I was there in 1970.

01:09:12.870 --> 01:09:16.790
We were doing the so-called
phased withdrawal.

01:09:16.790 --> 01:09:21.740
I couldn't see logically why
American troops were still going

01:09:21.740 --> 01:09:24.340
out on combat missions and dying.

01:09:24.340 --> 01:09:28.560
Um, so I protested the war.

01:09:28.560 --> 01:09:32.960
Came down here in the big
anti-war demonstration called Dewey

01:09:32.960 --> 01:09:35.150
Canyon III.

01:09:35.150 --> 01:09:42.290
And it was the first time since
the bonus marches in 1932,

01:09:42.290 --> 01:09:47.810
I believe it was, who came to
Washington to say, "Look at us.

01:09:47.810 --> 01:09:52.410
Get out of Vietnam, uh, now."

01:09:52.410 --> 01:09:55.120
Um, and I think it had an effect.

01:09:55.120 --> 01:09:57.330
I certainly hope it had an effect.

01:09:57.330 --> 01:10:02.220
But there was certainly
in me and I know in a lot

01:10:02.220 --> 01:10:06.930
of other folks the sense of
alienation, uh, in coming home.

01:10:06.930 --> 01:10:09.030
And I was not a combatant.

01:10:09.030 --> 01:10:11.770
Uh, when I was there, I
had top secret clearance.

01:10:11.770 --> 01:10:13.130
I could travel around.

01:10:13.130 --> 01:10:17.220
I spent a lot of time with
the 91st Evacuation Hospital

01:10:17.220 --> 01:10:20.930
up in a place called Chu Lai,
uh, with the docs and the nurses.

01:10:20.930 --> 01:10:28.070 position:56%
Saw as much as of the, uh,
debasement and the debris of war as,

01:10:28.070 --> 01:10:30.330
you know, most grunts did.

01:10:30.330 --> 01:10:35.490
And, you know -- and, as
Doc said, it changes you

01:10:35.490 --> 01:10:40.080
and unless you're there, you
really can't understand even

01:10:40.080 --> 01:10:44.130
if you watch the best war
movies that were ever made.

01:10:44.130 --> 01:10:46.090 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Let's talk about,
for a second, identifying some

01:10:46.090 --> 01:10:47.640
of the telltale signs of PTSD.

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:50.080
It's always helpful if you're
going to try and tackle a problem

01:10:50.080 --> 01:10:52.260
to at least understand the
problem you're up against.

01:10:52.260 --> 01:10:55.720 position:56%
From my understand, from my
experience from talking to veterans,

01:10:55.720 --> 01:10:58.650
alcohol, drug use, those
are about as common

01:10:58.650 --> 01:11:01.310
across the board telltale
signs you're going to have

01:11:01.310 --> 01:11:03.960
because of either withdrawal
or escapism.

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:07.170
Um, maybe not being
able to socialize.

01:11:07.170 --> 01:11:09.500
They'll be in a social setting
that, back when they were perhaps

01:11:09.500 --> 01:11:11.750
in their home town maybe
with some high school buddies

01:11:11.750 --> 01:11:13.980
and they just start yacking
about a football game,

01:11:13.980 --> 01:11:16.810
they feel out of place,
they don't contribute.

01:11:16.810 --> 01:11:20.350
Give me some other strong telltale
songs for anybody perhaps watching

01:11:20.350 --> 01:11:21.650
or anybody in the audience

01:11:21.650 --> 01:11:23.210
that maybe they have a loved
one that's going through this

01:11:23.210 --> 01:11:24.510
and they want to make
sure that they can

01:11:24.510 --> 01:11:27.040
at least identify what
it is they're up against?

01:11:27.040 --> 01:11:30.270
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Hyperarousal
certainly is one of

01:11:30.270 --> 01:11:31.780
and I'll bet every combat vet

01:11:31.780 --> 01:11:35.100
in this room knows exactly
what I'm talking about.

01:11:35.100 --> 01:11:36.540
It happened to me this morning.

01:11:36.540 --> 01:11:43.250
A colleague -- now I place
my desk so it faces the door.

01:11:43.250 --> 01:11:48.410
Now most, you know, um, office
management things says, "Well,

01:11:48.410 --> 01:11:51.370
that's kind of -- put it
to the side or whatever."

01:11:51.370 --> 01:11:55.720
I can't do that because even
with my desk facing the doorway,

01:11:55.720 --> 01:11:59.550
if I'm focused on reading something
or whatever and somebody just says,

01:11:59.550 --> 01:12:02.790
"Hi, Doc," it scares the
you know what out of me.

01:12:02.790 --> 01:12:06.070
And that can happen anywhere.

01:12:06.070 --> 01:12:10.150
If I'm focused on something
and people call my name

01:12:10.150 --> 01:12:13.440
or I hear a loud noise,
something like that,

01:12:13.440 --> 01:12:15.250
that's certainly a problem.

01:12:15.250 --> 01:12:20.770
The other thing has been mentioned
earlier in the conversation, uh,

01:12:20.770 --> 01:12:23.470
nightmares and flashbacks.

01:12:23.470 --> 01:12:26.940
And those are two different things.

01:12:26.940 --> 01:12:29.440
OK, you have nightmares
when you sleep at night.

01:12:29.440 --> 01:12:32.820
And they may be the same nightmare.

01:12:32.820 --> 01:12:40.660
Flashbacks happen any time and you
are back there because trauma is --

01:12:40.660 --> 01:12:42.430
and particularly severe trauma --

01:12:42.430 --> 01:12:46.710
can change the circuitry of
the brain so that certain --

01:12:46.710 --> 01:12:53.130
want to call them, uh -- uh --
triggers, will put you right back

01:12:53.130 --> 01:12:58.440
where a particular
traumatic event occurred.

01:12:58.440 --> 01:13:00.210
So those are a couple of other --

01:13:00.210 --> 01:13:01.510
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Does --
let me ask you this too.

01:13:01.510 --> 01:13:03.510
It's 42 years since
the end of the war.

01:13:03.510 --> 01:13:04.810
Have -- has in subsided?

01:13:04.810 --> 01:13:06.110
Has it gotten easier?

01:13:06.110 --> 01:13:08.640
Has it -- has it kind of freed
you a little bit, or is it right

01:13:08.640 --> 01:13:10.720
at the forefront as
it's always been?

01:13:10.720 --> 01:13:12.660
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Um,
there are a couple of --

01:13:12.660 --> 01:13:17.770
I don't want to go back to
Vietnam despite all the, uh,

01:13:17.770 --> 01:13:22.610
overtures in friendship and
Vietnam Veterans of America,

01:13:22.610 --> 01:13:24.780
where I work, has led the way.

01:13:24.780 --> 01:13:28.210
We have, um, a veteran's
initiative, which we can talk

01:13:28.210 --> 01:13:29.560
about another time another place.

01:13:29.560 --> 01:13:33.710
Uh, I don't want to go back
there because I am afraid

01:13:33.710 --> 01:13:38.800
that it will bring back stuff
that I've had to deal with, uh,

01:13:38.800 --> 01:13:41.760
through therapy and
through rap groups and stuff

01:13:41.760 --> 01:13:44.230 position:56%
and I don't want through that again.

01:13:44.230 --> 01:13:49.890
But I do have a couple of recurring
nightmares that I can't seem

01:13:49.890 --> 01:13:54.590
to get rid of and they were
pretty traumatic situations.

01:13:54.590 --> 01:13:56.510
So -- but they come
back and it's usually

01:13:56.510 --> 01:13:58.860
when I'm -- I'm stressed out.

01:13:58.860 --> 01:14:00.160
OK?

01:14:00.160 --> 01:14:01.460
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Tim?

01:14:01.460 --> 01:14:03.670
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: I think anger is,
uh, a main one speaking for myself.

01:14:03.670 --> 01:14:04.970
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
You explode quickly?

01:14:04.970 --> 01:14:06.270
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Absolutely.

01:14:06.270 --> 01:14:10.360
You know, I've obviously found ways
to, uh, you know, combat that, um,

01:14:10.360 --> 01:14:12.950
you know, through group
therapy and stuff like that.

01:14:12.950 --> 01:14:14.250
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Now
let me ask you this.

01:14:14.250 --> 01:14:16.550 position:56%
The loved ones around you before
they knew what they were up against,

01:14:16.550 --> 01:14:18.730
were they just saying, "You know
what, he's got a hairpin trigger.

01:14:18.730 --> 01:14:20.030
That's just how he's always been?"

01:14:20.030 --> 01:14:23.390 position:56%
They try and rationalize away the
behavior not to try to cope with it?

01:14:23.390 --> 01:14:24.690
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Yeah.

01:14:24.690 --> 01:14:25.990
I mean, they didn't really
understand it, like I said earlier.

01:14:25.990 --> 01:14:28.650
They just kind of thought,
like, uh, you know --

01:14:28.650 --> 01:14:30.160
they knew something
was wrong, but, again,

01:14:30.160 --> 01:14:31.460
they didn't know what was wrong.

01:14:31.460 --> 01:14:32.760
They didn't know what
they were looking at.

01:14:32.760 --> 01:14:34.580
They didn't know what
they were facing.

01:14:34.580 --> 01:14:37.870
And, you know, anger, I think
it stems from, you know,

01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:40.540
when you come back you have these
-- this sort of -- like I --

01:14:40.540 --> 01:14:42.960
I call it like your standing
in the shallows of the ocean

01:14:42.960 --> 01:14:44.790
and that wave just
keeps hitting you.

01:14:44.790 --> 01:14:47.680
And it's a wave of these
emotions that keeps coming.

01:14:47.680 --> 01:14:50.230
You you've never felt this
stuff before so you get angry.

01:14:50.230 --> 01:14:52.320
You get angry because you can't
navigate through your day.

01:14:52.320 --> 01:14:54.150
You can't be that social person.

01:14:54.150 --> 01:14:57.160
You can't go hang out with the guys
and talk about the football game.

01:14:57.160 --> 01:15:01.740
You know? You would rather isolate
-- at least this is what I did.

01:15:01.740 --> 01:15:03.040
I isolated.

01:15:03.040 --> 01:15:05.530
I used drugs and alcohol because
they're 100% effective every time.

01:15:05.530 --> 01:15:08.110
They numb all those emotions.

01:15:08.110 --> 01:15:09.410
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
You know, we've --

01:15:09.410 --> 01:15:11.630
as a nation, we've been at it
for 240 years and we've been

01:15:11.630 --> 01:15:13.360
at war a lot of that time.

01:15:13.360 --> 01:15:15.670
And, you know, all throughout the
generations from the Civil War

01:15:15.670 --> 01:15:17.920
to World War II, they would call it
shell shock or they just call it,

01:15:17.920 --> 01:15:19.220
"Oh, he's being quiet," whatever.

01:15:19.220 --> 01:15:22.020
I mean, now we call it PTSD because
we've identified it as a problem.

01:15:22.020 --> 01:15:25.000
But this is a problem that has
plagued our returning warriors

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:27.210
since we've been at
it in the battlefield.

01:15:27.210 --> 01:15:29.240
And, you know, Judge, I'm just
curious, some of the things

01:15:29.240 --> 01:15:30.790
that you have seen, because
I'm sure you had a lot

01:15:30.790 --> 01:15:33.330
of cases come before you
where you have telltale signs

01:15:33.330 --> 01:15:35.250
that run from A to Z on this one.

01:15:35.250 --> 01:15:38.440
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: All -- all of the
substance abuse issues are there,

01:15:38.440 --> 01:15:40.830 position:56%
of course, and a lot of times
that's just a reaction to the anger.

01:15:40.830 --> 01:15:43.780
I think that the -- really
the underlying current

01:15:43.780 --> 01:15:47.270
that affects the most is
-- is just plain anger.

01:15:47.270 --> 01:15:50.490
You know, I remember as we're
getting ready to climb on a C-17

01:15:50.490 --> 01:15:54.980 position:56%
to leave Afghanistan after that time
some of the younger folks, again,

01:15:54.980 --> 01:15:59.740
these young 11-B infantry
troopers, you know, "Gosh, we --

01:15:59.740 --> 01:16:03.000
we went to Afghanistan and the rest
of the country went to Walmart."

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:04.990
It's almost a resentment
that -- that --

01:16:04.990 --> 01:16:07.880
that when you get back you kind of
resent the fact that you get there.

01:16:07.880 --> 01:16:12.000 position:56%
And, of course, on the return of
the Iraq and the Afghan guys that --

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:14.100
it's much different
from the Vietnam era.

01:16:14.100 --> 01:16:17.860
You -- you hear, you know,
"Thank you for your service," um,

01:16:17.860 --> 01:16:21.420
an awful lot and I have to admit,
yeah, I was angry when I got back.

01:16:21.420 --> 01:16:24.310
I -- the Army was still pretty bad

01:16:24.310 --> 01:16:26.190
about how they handled
you when you came back.

01:16:26.190 --> 01:16:28.490 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: But -- let me ask
you -- all of you -- do you think --

01:16:28.490 --> 01:16:32.490
because the military spends
gazillions of dollars on everything

01:16:32.490 --> 01:16:35.960
from perfecting the ways
of killing people to trying

01:16:35.960 --> 01:16:38.990
to understand the warriors
to artificial intelligence.

01:16:38.990 --> 01:16:42.090
I'm just curious, is there
any kind of mechanism

01:16:42.090 --> 01:16:44.880
that anyone could provide
to ready them

01:16:44.880 --> 01:16:46.180
for what they're really
going to experience?

01:16:46.180 --> 01:16:49.030
I know they train them for combat,
but training somebody for combat

01:16:49.030 --> 01:16:52.220
and experiencing and living through
combat, totally different things.

01:16:52.220 --> 01:16:54.680
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Well, one of
the things is -- and it's --

01:16:54.680 --> 01:16:57.500
it's spot on what you just said.

01:16:57.500 --> 01:17:01.410
They train you for
situations that threaten you,

01:17:01.410 --> 01:17:06.320
that put you in a sense
of danger and you react.

01:17:06.320 --> 01:17:10.460
And if you follow that training,
chances are you're going

01:17:10.460 --> 01:17:13.100
to make it through that situation.

01:17:13.100 --> 01:17:18.940
When you come home, OK, you have to
go back to the old way of thinking,

01:17:18.940 --> 01:17:24.510
which is just because
Fido pooped on the floor,

01:17:24.510 --> 01:17:27.880
that is not a life
threatening situation.

01:17:27.880 --> 01:17:32.290
But, OK, you react that way.

01:17:32.290 --> 01:17:37.600 position:56%
And is one of the things they should
consider, in my humble opinion,

01:17:37.600 --> 01:17:41.480
and Canada did it for a while
and the UK did it for a while,

01:17:41.480 --> 01:17:47.360
is they put their troops in
sort of a -- a decompression.

01:17:47.360 --> 01:17:50.850
I believe it was the UK --
or was it the Canadians --

01:17:50.850 --> 01:17:53.090
had a place on Cypress.

01:17:53.090 --> 01:17:56.890
OK? And some cases there were,
you know, married couples

01:17:56.890 --> 01:18:02.280
and stuff could -- and they
helped them decompress, um,

01:18:02.280 --> 01:18:05.380
as sort of like a post-service
boot camp.

01:18:05.380 --> 01:18:10.620 position:56%
Now whether that would get a lot of
support down the street, um, or not,

01:18:10.620 --> 01:18:12.980
you know, that's -- that's
neither here nor there.

01:18:12.980 --> 01:18:19.310
But we could do something better
on the end of it to get us back

01:18:19.310 --> 01:18:21.920
in terms of the transition system.

01:18:21.920 --> 01:18:23.220
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Please.

01:18:23.220 --> 01:18:26.060
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: So, you know, I
work for [inaudible] and my job is

01:18:26.060 --> 01:18:28.990
to really identify gaps, you
know, and throughout the continuum

01:18:28.990 --> 01:18:32.530
of criminal justice to improve
outcomes for veterans and one

01:18:32.530 --> 01:18:35.970
of the interviews I was conducting,
uh, with a veteran, um --

01:18:35.970 --> 01:18:38.990 position:56%
you know, he said, "They trained me,
you know, to go to basic training.

01:18:38.990 --> 01:18:40.310
They trained me to
go to my first duty.

01:18:40.310 --> 01:18:43.300 position:56%
They trained me to go to combat, but
they didn't train me to come home."

01:18:43.300 --> 01:18:45.650
And I think that that's
a real gap in our system.

01:18:45.650 --> 01:18:48.200
I always, um -- couple
-- couple points.

01:18:48.200 --> 01:18:53.240 position:56%
One, um, we need to reduce the
stigma for soldiers to ask for help.

01:18:53.240 --> 01:18:55.620
We need to do a better
job of helping them.

01:18:55.620 --> 01:18:59.140
And I think that why does the
first opportunity to intervene

01:18:59.140 --> 01:19:01.440
in their life have to be
the criminal justice system?

01:19:01.440 --> 01:19:04.620
I think that if we can do, uh --
I think there's specific funding

01:19:04.620 --> 01:19:08.810
with DOD to, um, you know, to
train people, to pay for uniforms,

01:19:08.810 --> 01:19:10.610
to, um, you know, travel.

01:19:10.610 --> 01:19:13.820
But there's no specific
funding to come home

01:19:13.820 --> 01:19:15.770
and to help them acclimate home.

01:19:15.770 --> 01:19:19.290
And I think that that's a real
gap, um, that we need to address.

01:19:19.290 --> 01:19:20.590
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Let
me just -- go ahead.

01:19:20.590 --> 01:19:22.530
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: And I think
there's a real problem also.

01:19:22.530 --> 01:19:26.650
The military has changed, although,
it's still defect in a lot of ways

01:19:26.650 --> 01:19:29.590
like it was in World War II.

01:19:29.590 --> 01:19:31.760
I say this because I've
done some clinical work

01:19:31.760 --> 01:19:35.930
with Delta Force people
and -- and SEALs.

01:19:35.930 --> 01:19:37.540
Some said it earlier.

01:19:37.540 --> 01:19:41.620
Most Americans don't appreciate
the tempo of operations,

01:19:41.620 --> 01:19:44.820
um, over in the big sandbox.

01:19:44.820 --> 01:19:48.110
It's -- I mean, heavy duty intense.

01:19:48.110 --> 01:19:52.540
The general -- the general and, uh,
my colleague sitting next to me,

01:19:52.540 --> 01:19:54.700
the judge, will tell
you what it's like.

01:19:54.700 --> 01:19:59.250
But the fact of the matter
is that these folks are

01:19:59.250 --> 01:20:02.670
under such intense --
particularly in our --

01:20:02.670 --> 01:20:04.730
in our special ops groups --

01:20:04.730 --> 01:20:11.140 position:56%
are under such intense pressure that
life back here is not very realistic

01:20:11.140 --> 01:20:13.260
to them when they come home.

01:20:13.260 --> 01:20:15.410
They try and adjust.

01:20:15.410 --> 01:20:20.010
OK? But why do so many of
our special ops people feel

01:20:20.010 --> 01:20:22.350
that they're more at
home back there?

01:20:22.350 --> 01:20:25.320
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Let me
ask this question, too,

01:20:25.320 --> 01:20:28.310
because I know we live in an ADD
society and I don't mean to use

01:20:28.310 --> 01:20:31.870 position:56%
that term pejoratively, but I think
it's true that you walk around today

01:20:31.870 --> 01:20:34.430 position:56%
and you'll see nine out of 10 people
walking around with their phones.

01:20:34.430 --> 01:20:35.750
They're connected to
I don't know what.

01:20:35.750 --> 01:20:38.000
I mean, maybe there's a
text they can't go without

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:41.500
or a headline they can't go
without, but folks who are warriors

01:20:41.500 --> 01:20:44.830
who have been in combat -- and
I've heard this probably 99%

01:20:44.830 --> 01:20:47.210
of the time -- for
them time stands still.

01:20:47.210 --> 01:20:48.510
Time slows down.

01:20:48.510 --> 01:20:51.530
The continuum just absolutely
comes to a grinding halt.

01:20:51.530 --> 01:20:54.070
And when they come home they feel
as though the world is running

01:20:54.070 --> 01:20:57.140
by them 1,000 miles an hour
and they're stuck in a spot

01:20:57.140 --> 01:21:00.050
where they just need
somebody to talk to.

01:21:00.050 --> 01:21:02.960
So now let's get into the resources
because we have the veterans court,

01:21:02.960 --> 01:21:05.930
which is a system that
has started to spread,

01:21:05.930 --> 01:21:07.500 position:56%
but certainly could grow a lot more.

01:21:07.500 --> 01:21:12.170 position:56%
But what are the resources available
to people especially with PTSD

01:21:12.170 --> 01:21:14.950
and TBIs coming home that
they could reach out to

01:21:14.950 --> 01:21:16.250
that would help their experience?

01:21:16.250 --> 01:21:18.460
Because we have folks that,
you know, are watching on TV

01:21:18.460 --> 01:21:20.920
and perhaps they're sitting there
saying, "I didn't get out of bed

01:21:20.920 --> 01:21:22.400
until 11 O'clock this morning.

01:21:22.400 --> 01:21:24.740
I don't know why I'd
want to get out of bed."

01:21:24.740 --> 01:21:26.480 position:56%
What resource can they reach out to?

01:21:26.480 --> 01:21:27.840
Because there's a lot of them.

01:21:27.840 --> 01:21:29.270
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: There are a lot.

01:21:29.270 --> 01:21:32.110
Um, lots of good community.

01:21:32.110 --> 01:21:35.200
I would, uh, say for those --

01:21:35.200 --> 01:21:40.600
and we know that because of
all the media surrounding a lot

01:21:40.600 --> 01:21:41.900
of the problems with the VA,

01:21:41.900 --> 01:21:45.840
they don't trust the VA
hospitals for whatever reason.

01:21:45.840 --> 01:21:47.440
The Vet Centers.

01:21:47.440 --> 01:21:49.210
Try the Vet Centers!

01:21:49.210 --> 01:21:56.170
Because they are the most cost
efficient mental health operation

01:21:56.170 --> 01:21:57.470
in the VA system.

01:21:57.470 --> 01:21:59.200
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: And they -- and
all they have to do is just walk in

01:21:59.200 --> 01:22:00.820
and say, "I just need
someone to talk to."

01:22:00.820 --> 01:22:02.120
They don't have to
fill out the paperwork

01:22:02.120 --> 01:22:03.420
and go through the red tape.

01:22:03.420 --> 01:22:04.720
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Right.

01:22:04.720 --> 01:22:07.430
Your mental health information
that you choose to share

01:22:07.430 --> 01:22:09.680
at a Vet Center doesn't go

01:22:09.680 --> 01:22:13.550
to the mothership unless
you sign a consent.

01:22:13.550 --> 01:22:17.840
OK? And, for those vet centers
that have the resources,

01:22:17.840 --> 01:22:21.450
meaning the money and the people,
they also can work with families.

01:22:21.450 --> 01:22:26.050
And that's a big deal
because the big hospitals

01:22:26.050 --> 01:22:27.840 position:56%
and stuff aren't allowed to do that.

01:22:27.840 --> 01:22:30.640
There are some programs and
kinds of -- but the vet centers,

01:22:30.640 --> 01:22:32.380
I highly recommend the vet centers.

01:22:32.380 --> 01:22:35.670
And a lot of the team leaders,
what they call the director

01:22:35.670 --> 01:22:39.170
at vet centers, are
combat veterans themselves.

01:22:39.170 --> 01:22:43.650
And that's what made it such
a success that 10 years ago,

01:22:43.650 --> 01:22:48.100
15 years ago I guess now because
we've been in this latest morass

01:22:48.100 --> 01:22:52.080
for that long, most of the
team leaders were combat

01:22:52.080 --> 01:22:54.010
Vietnam veterans.

01:22:54.010 --> 01:22:55.350
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Bernie?

01:22:55.350 --> 01:23:00.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: There are 330 or
so VTCs, veteran's treatment courts.

01:23:00.320 --> 01:23:05.260
There are exactly 300 Vet
Centers, but they're located mostly

01:23:05.260 --> 01:23:10.340 position:56%
in cities, uh, in strip malls, uh --

01:23:10.340 --> 01:23:12.900
there should be twice
that number at least.

01:23:12.900 --> 01:23:16.400
That's where resources need to go.

01:23:16.400 --> 01:23:24.220
Uh, but it's also -- we depend upon
the VA to -- and the government --

01:23:24.220 --> 01:23:28.630
to help those who are
several combat wounded, uh,

01:23:28.630 --> 01:23:33.660
to help them fiscally,
physically, mentally.

01:23:33.660 --> 01:23:39.750
Spiritually, you have to depend
on the community that you live in.

01:23:39.750 --> 01:23:45.150
And a lot of Americans
prefer not to deal with that.

01:23:45.150 --> 01:23:46.920
Stop and think about this.

01:23:46.920 --> 01:23:51.120
In the Second World War when the
population of this country was

01:23:51.120 --> 01:23:55.930
about 130,000,000 or so,
16,000,000 Americans,

01:23:55.930 --> 01:23:59.080
men and women, were in uniform.

01:23:59.080 --> 01:24:02.230
Just about everyone in the
country was somehow involved

01:24:02.230 --> 01:24:03.530
in the war effort.

01:24:03.530 --> 01:24:05.940
I don't know what the
numbers were for Korea.

01:24:05.940 --> 01:24:08.740
In Vietnam it had shrunk
to something

01:24:08.740 --> 01:24:12.530
like 9%, some people said 4%.

01:24:12.530 --> 01:24:19.000
Right now less than 1/5
of 1% of Americans --

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:22.100
now we're not talking about
5 year old children --

01:24:22.100 --> 01:24:28.620
but of Americans I guess 18 or
above serve in the military.

01:24:28.620 --> 01:24:32.420
This is a tiny number.

01:24:32.420 --> 01:24:33.800
People go through college.

01:24:33.800 --> 01:24:36.700
They don't have to worry about
being drafted or anything.

01:24:36.700 --> 01:24:40.500
When we were in school, that
was, you know, one of the things

01:24:40.500 --> 01:24:45.390
that kept us in school as
long as we had the grades.

01:24:45.390 --> 01:24:48.580
But people come home and a lot

01:24:48.580 --> 01:24:53.060
of times there's something
missing in community.

01:24:53.060 --> 01:24:58.690
Uh, which is tragic and it
leads to more [inaudible].

01:24:58.690 --> 01:25:03.110
People aren't welcomed home into
the bosom of a grateful nation

01:25:03.110 --> 01:25:08.110
because too often the nation is
not grateful for a war without end.

01:25:08.110 --> 01:25:10.330
And that's what we had in Vietnam.

01:25:10.330 --> 01:25:11.680
That's what we have now.

01:25:11.680 --> 01:25:12.980
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Is it a --

01:25:12.980 --> 01:25:15.150
&gt;&gt; Melissa Fitzgerald:
There's a veterans crisis line

01:25:15.150 --> 01:25:16.450
if you wouldn't mind
giving out that number.

01:25:16.450 --> 01:25:17.750
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Sure.

01:25:17.750 --> 01:25:21.360
Um, the Veterans Crisis Line is
another resource you can turn to.

01:25:21.360 --> 01:25:25.230
It's 1-800-273-8255.

01:25:25.230 --> 01:25:27.690
And then when you call that
number you can just press 1.

01:25:27.690 --> 01:25:28.990
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Press 1.

01:25:28.990 --> 01:25:30.290
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
Tim, let me go to you

01:25:30.290 --> 01:25:32.490 position:56%
because you came back from this war.

01:25:32.490 --> 01:25:35.700
And you had said -- "Hope"
was the word you used.

01:25:35.700 --> 01:25:38.740
Um, the veterans that I talked
to coming back from this war,

01:25:38.740 --> 01:25:42.290 position:56%
they seemed to think that the people
at home, while they're grateful

01:25:42.290 --> 01:25:45.160
for their service, they don't
understand what their service

01:25:45.160 --> 01:25:46.460
was for.

01:25:46.460 --> 01:25:49.130
And then the translation to you is
then, "What the hell was I doing?"

01:25:49.130 --> 01:25:51.850
Is that a part of what you
processed or are still processing?

01:25:51.850 --> 01:25:55.660 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: I think for a short
period of time I went through that.

01:25:55.660 --> 01:25:57.300
Not so much now.

01:25:57.300 --> 01:26:02.840
Um, to me, what I did over there
was standing shoulder-to-shoulder

01:26:02.840 --> 01:26:05.990
with my brothers and
sisters in arms.

01:26:05.990 --> 01:26:07.970
You know, we -- we did
what we had to do to get

01:26:07.970 --> 01:26:10.370
through every single day
to protect one another.

01:26:10.370 --> 01:26:13.310
And, you know, I don't get to
far into it as far as, you know,

01:26:13.310 --> 01:26:15.180
political why we did what we did.

01:26:15.180 --> 01:26:16.480
Um, that's not my concern.

01:26:16.480 --> 01:26:20.080
My concern then was protecting the
people to the right and the left

01:26:20.080 --> 01:26:22.000
of me and that still stands today.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:23.680
That's what I do here
in my community.

01:26:23.680 --> 01:26:26.030
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Did you have
a clearly defined objective

01:26:26.030 --> 01:26:28.730
as a warrior in battle?

01:26:28.730 --> 01:26:31.010
Did you understand day-to-day
what it is you were trying

01:26:31.010 --> 01:26:32.810
to do or accomplish?

01:26:32.810 --> 01:26:34.110
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Yes.

01:26:34.110 --> 01:26:35.990
You know, I, uh -- I had --

01:26:35.990 --> 01:26:40.700
I was a sergeant and my job was to
protect the people underneath me.

01:26:40.700 --> 01:26:43.840
And that was my main
objective every single day.

01:26:43.840 --> 01:26:46.460
Um, I ran convoys over there.

01:26:46.460 --> 01:26:48.730
I was a 50 Cal gunner
on top of a Humvee.

01:26:48.730 --> 01:26:51.500
My objective was to get the
people in that convoy from point A

01:26:51.500 --> 01:26:55.410
to point B -- point A to point
B. That was my projective.

01:26:55.410 --> 01:26:59.070
Um, there are also good
people in the country

01:26:59.070 --> 01:27:01.830
of Iraq who need protection.

01:27:01.830 --> 01:27:04.130
And we protected them as well.

01:27:07.080 --> 01:27:09.750
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Bob Birdnow
[assumed spelling] is here

01:27:09.750 --> 01:27:11.600
in the audience.

01:27:11.600 --> 01:27:14.590
Bob comes from Quincy,
Massachusetts.

01:27:14.590 --> 01:27:22.100
Um, for the past several
years he and I, his wife,

01:27:22.100 --> 01:27:26.800
couple of other folks, have gone
up to Quincy at the end of April

01:27:26.800 --> 01:27:31.790
for a ceremony, United
Combat Veterans of Quincy,

01:27:31.790 --> 01:27:35.210
95% of whom served
in the Marine Corps.

01:27:35.210 --> 01:27:36.510
Talk about brotherhood.

01:27:36.510 --> 01:27:37.820
There you have it.

01:27:37.820 --> 01:27:44.380
Uh, it used to be a handful of guys
would go down to this clock tower,

01:27:44.380 --> 01:27:50.320
uh, which had the names inscribed
on it of 45 of Quincy's --

01:27:50.320 --> 01:27:53.590
the sons of Quincy who died
during the Vietnam War.

01:27:53.590 --> 01:27:56.490
They'd read the names
and then they would go

01:27:56.490 --> 01:28:00.320
to this fairly awful
Chinese restaurant, uh,

01:28:00.320 --> 01:28:04.160
but there was a certain
loyalty there.

01:28:04.160 --> 01:28:12.660 position:56%
When they added Bob's brother's name
to the -- the roster of the dead,

01:28:12.660 --> 01:28:16.410
uh, things I think
started to change.

01:28:16.410 --> 01:28:20.800
You had a situation where more
and more people started, uh --

01:28:20.800 --> 01:28:26.310
resident -- a son of Quincy, rather
-- came to give you keynote speech.

01:28:26.310 --> 01:28:32.190
Here you have a situation where the
community embraces those who served

01:28:32.190 --> 01:28:34.670
and tries to help them heal.

01:28:34.670 --> 01:28:39.440
It's a small part of the community,
but it's always, it seems,

01:28:39.440 --> 01:28:42.630
veterans helping veterans.

01:28:42.630 --> 01:28:46.920
Those who didn't serve, you
don't get it the same way.

01:28:46.920 --> 01:28:48.290
A lot of veterans -- a lot

01:28:48.290 --> 01:28:50.960
of non-veterans will
say, "Welcome home."

01:28:50.960 --> 01:28:52.260
That's nice.

01:28:52.260 --> 01:28:53.560
"Thank you for your service."

01:28:53.560 --> 01:28:54.860
That's nice.

01:28:54.860 --> 01:28:57.270
But they don't understand it.

01:28:57.270 --> 01:29:01.430
When a veteran says that to
someone who's come back, it has --

01:29:01.430 --> 01:29:03.350
it's a different context almost.

01:29:03.350 --> 01:29:10.210
And in Quincy, it's an
example of what I think a lot

01:29:10.210 --> 01:29:14.520
of other communities can
do and should do not only

01:29:14.520 --> 01:29:17.920
for the younger guys,
but for all veterans.

01:29:17.920 --> 01:29:19.830
You know, a lot of the
veteran's treatment courts,

01:29:19.830 --> 01:29:24.360
there are more Vietnam era
veterans than there are Iraq

01:29:24.360 --> 01:29:25.810
and Afghanistan veterans.

01:29:25.810 --> 01:29:27.110
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Right.

01:29:27.110 --> 01:29:28.410
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: When
you were mentioning, uh --

01:29:28.410 --> 01:29:34.210
uh, or in the film clip we saw, 22
veterans commit suicide every day.

01:29:34.210 --> 01:29:35.510
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Twenty.

01:29:35.510 --> 01:29:36.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: It said 22 there.

01:29:36.810 --> 01:29:38.110
But --

01:29:38.110 --> 01:29:39.410
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Even
one a day is too much.

01:29:39.410 --> 01:29:40.710
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: Correct!

01:29:40.710 --> 01:29:44.890
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Something like
70% of those veterans are age 55 --

01:29:44.890 --> 01:29:46.190
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: And older.

01:29:46.190 --> 01:29:47.490
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Or older.

01:29:47.490 --> 01:29:49.800
They're not the young
people who came back.

01:29:49.800 --> 01:29:51.770
The connotation was, "Here,

01:29:51.770 --> 01:29:55.500
look at these damaged people
who've -- who are coming home."

01:29:55.500 --> 01:29:57.480
A lot of the people
who are among that --

01:29:57.480 --> 01:29:58.780
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Well, one

01:29:58.780 --> 01:30:01.370 position:56%
of the largest homeless
populations right now in our country

01:30:01.370 --> 01:30:03.540
of veterans is the Vietnam War.

01:30:03.540 --> 01:30:04.840
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Oh, yeah.

01:30:04.840 --> 01:30:07.690
&gt;&gt; Tom Berger: And -- and --
excuse me -- I would argue --

01:30:07.690 --> 01:30:11.370
here's a discussion point,
OK, because not all of you are

01:30:11.370 --> 01:30:14.020
in the audience and are veterans.

01:30:14.020 --> 01:30:19.530 position:56%
What Bernie said about the
veterans in the community is fine --

01:30:19.530 --> 01:30:23.270
to draw veterans together.

01:30:23.270 --> 01:30:27.880
What I would say is instead
of having veterans night

01:30:27.880 --> 01:30:34.130
at the ballpark, take the
resources that are used to do that,

01:30:34.130 --> 01:30:39.930 position:56%
make sure that your community mental
health office is not only open 24/7

01:30:39.930 --> 01:30:43.050
several days a week, but
is staffed with somebody

01:30:43.050 --> 01:30:48.910
that can handle military
PTSD , or MST .

01:30:48.910 --> 01:30:53.820 position:56%
That is something that the community
can do to help our veterans.

01:30:53.820 --> 01:30:55.120
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Greg,
let me ask you this.

01:30:55.120 --> 01:30:57.690 position:56%
Especially now we're talking about
resources that may be tightening up.

01:30:57.690 --> 01:31:00.320
Budgets may be changing and
there may not be as much money

01:31:00.320 --> 01:31:02.300
to help fund some of the
programs that are currently there.

01:31:02.300 --> 01:31:03.600
What can people do?

01:31:03.600 --> 01:31:05.680
And I especially want to
deal with folks in rural --

01:31:05.680 --> 01:31:07.870
I'm from a small town
outside of California.

01:31:07.870 --> 01:31:11.880
I know in those communities a lot
of our population ended up going

01:31:11.880 --> 01:31:13.440
in enlisting into the militaries.

01:31:13.440 --> 01:31:15.680
So what do folks in
rural communities do?

01:31:15.680 --> 01:31:18.990 position:56%
How do they deal with returning
warriors who are having these issues

01:31:18.990 --> 01:31:21.450
who become somewhat isolated,
who perhaps maybe turn

01:31:21.450 --> 01:31:23.120
to drugs or alcohol as an escape?

01:31:23.120 --> 01:31:24.420
What do you do for them?

01:31:24.420 --> 01:31:26.840 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: Well, I think, um,
number one, the National Institute

01:31:26.840 --> 01:31:29.180
of Corrections provides training
and technical assistance.

01:31:29.180 --> 01:31:30.940
So if your jurisdictional
out there is looking

01:31:30.940 --> 01:31:33.540
to implement a veterans
treatment court program, um,

01:31:33.540 --> 01:31:38.350
they can contact NIC, uh,
at NICIC.gov and, you know,

01:31:38.350 --> 01:31:40.680 position:56%
give us a call and we can talk about
what your issues are and whether

01:31:40.680 --> 01:31:42.550
or not you want to start
a veterans treatment court

01:31:42.550 --> 01:31:45.870
or some other specific programming
either in a jail or a prison.

01:31:45.870 --> 01:31:50.110
Um -- or they can contact
Justice for Vets, uh,

01:31:50.110 --> 01:31:53.700
or there's grants available, um,
through the Federal Government.

01:31:53.700 --> 01:31:57.870
Um, but what I would say is you
have to understand your population.

01:31:57.870 --> 01:31:59.770
And I think data drives
a lot of decisions

01:31:59.770 --> 01:32:01.340
in our jurisdictions
across the country.

01:32:01.340 --> 01:32:05.050
So if you can figure out how many
veterans you have in your jail

01:32:05.050 --> 01:32:08.640
or on your probation caseloads,
I think that that could help lead

01:32:08.640 --> 01:32:12.090
to -- you know -- warranting a
program in your jurisdiction.

01:32:12.090 --> 01:32:13.940
Then don't just ask,
"Are you a veteran?"

01:32:13.940 --> 01:32:16.260
because sometimes they
think you are only a veteran

01:32:16.260 --> 01:32:17.560
if you serve in combat.

01:32:17.560 --> 01:32:18.950
You have to say, "Have you
served in the military?"

01:32:18.950 --> 01:32:20.900
That's the key question to ask.

01:32:20.900 --> 01:32:23.770
And so once you've justified your
programming, a lot of times --

01:32:23.770 --> 01:32:25.600
and Judge Peterson, I think
you can speak to this --

01:32:25.600 --> 01:32:28.600
you can create something
with the exciting resources.

01:32:28.600 --> 01:32:30.130
Um, I don't know if you want to --

01:32:30.130 --> 01:32:31.430
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Yeah.

01:32:31.430 --> 01:32:34.110
I -- I -- I'm dying to know like
right now if we had 5,000 judges

01:32:34.110 --> 01:32:36.250
from across the country that are
just sitting here watching this,

01:32:36.250 --> 01:32:40.280
what would you tell them about how
things should at least be modified

01:32:40.280 --> 01:32:42.840
in order to deal with the growing
population of returning vets

01:32:42.840 --> 01:32:44.920
who may be dealing with
some of these issues?

01:32:44.920 --> 01:32:46.250
&gt;&gt; Vance Peterson: Well,
I'd tell them first,

01:32:46.250 --> 01:32:48.360
"You're going to prosecute
these guys anyway.

01:32:48.360 --> 01:32:50.280
You're -- you're going
to prosecute them.

01:32:50.280 --> 01:32:51.580
You're going to defend them.

01:32:51.580 --> 01:32:52.880
They're going to be charged.

01:32:52.880 --> 01:32:54.180
They're going to have a
probation officer involved.

01:32:54.180 --> 01:32:56.960
You're going to have a court
-- court clerk pull the file.

01:32:56.960 --> 01:32:59.230
Why don't you put them
all on the same docket?

01:32:59.230 --> 01:33:02.400
It doesn't cost you
any more to do that.

01:33:02.400 --> 01:33:06.210
And, from that, then you can
develop a veteran's court docket.

01:33:06.210 --> 01:33:08.940
And then you can start
looking into local resources."

01:33:08.940 --> 01:33:11.510
At one point in time I
remember talking to Judge Russel

01:33:11.510 --> 01:33:15.030
and there was a -- a concern
about making cookie cutter courts,

01:33:15.030 --> 01:33:16.930
all the veterans courts
would look alike.

01:33:16.930 --> 01:33:19.970
The reality was that every
jurisdiction is different.

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:21.620
Everybody has a different
group of veterans.

01:33:21.620 --> 01:33:24.480
In Lewiston, Idaho,
90% of their veterans

01:33:24.480 --> 01:33:26.240
in veteran's courts are marines.

01:33:26.240 --> 01:33:29.420
In our jurisdiction
it's about 60% Army,

01:33:29.420 --> 01:33:31.560
although we have an Air Force base.

01:33:31.560 --> 01:33:34.320
Some courts will handle
felony level events.

01:33:34.320 --> 01:33:36.280
Some courts will only
handle misdemeanor events.

01:33:36.280 --> 01:33:38.520
Some folks do a combination.

01:33:38.520 --> 01:33:42.090
But you can do this -- you can put
these programs together and set

01:33:42.090 --> 01:33:44.160
up a docket and it
doesn't cost you anything.

01:33:44.160 --> 01:33:45.890
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: You're talking
about making resources available

01:33:45.890 --> 01:33:48.030
so that they're going to be charged
with their crime and they're going

01:33:48.030 --> 01:33:50.580
through the judicial system,
but, at the same time,

01:33:50.580 --> 01:33:52.530
you're going to have
a peer one-on-one

01:33:52.530 --> 01:33:53.970
with a vet talking to these folks?

01:33:53.970 --> 01:33:57.420 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Vance Peterson: And each one of
the courts has a mentor type system.

01:33:57.420 --> 01:34:00.410
Each one of the courts has
developed their own particularized

01:34:00.410 --> 01:34:01.710
mentor system.

01:34:01.710 --> 01:34:04.600
We developed a forum and the
forum meets once a month.

01:34:04.600 --> 01:34:09.470 position:56%
Every veteran is basically sentenced
to attend 12 -- or six forums.

01:34:09.470 --> 01:34:11.690
They're given 24 months
of probation,

01:34:11.690 --> 01:34:14.070
you attend six forums,
it's only 18 months.

01:34:14.070 --> 01:34:16.550
You lose a month of probation
every time you attend a forum.

01:34:16.550 --> 01:34:18.780
If you attend 12 forums,
you're done.

01:34:18.780 --> 01:34:20.370
So the incentive is
to come to the forum.

01:34:20.370 --> 01:34:22.490
At the forum we feed them.

01:34:22.490 --> 01:34:23.940
We give them a dinner.

01:34:23.940 --> 01:34:28.360
Then we have them -- there are set
up a bunch of different resources,

01:34:28.360 --> 01:34:31.340
community resources for child
support, department of licensing

01:34:31.340 --> 01:34:34.610
for driver's licenses,
landlord tenant attorneys.

01:34:34.610 --> 01:34:38.040
We put every resource available
to a veteran in one room.

01:34:38.040 --> 01:34:39.950
After they're done going
through the resource portion,

01:34:39.950 --> 01:34:42.820
they go through two, one
hour group therapy sessions.

01:34:42.820 --> 01:34:47.290
And with that, um, they then get
through the program in 12 months --

01:34:47.290 --> 01:34:48.590
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
And let me stop you.

01:34:48.590 --> 01:34:49.910
And a lot of these resources
you're talking about,

01:34:49.910 --> 01:34:52.080
in most cases it's a phone
call because they'd be willing

01:34:52.080 --> 01:34:54.810
to volunteer their time and service
because of who we're talking about,

01:34:54.810 --> 01:34:56.110
the population we're talking about?

01:34:56.110 --> 01:34:57.410
&gt;&gt; Vance Peterson: Yes.

01:34:57.410 --> 01:34:58.710
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
Greg, you had something?

01:34:58.710 --> 01:35:00.010
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: Yeah.

01:35:00.010 --> 01:35:01.310
I want to -- I want to say
a couple different things.

01:35:01.310 --> 01:35:02.610
Number one, um, you can look
at Veteran Treatment Courts,

01:35:02.610 --> 01:35:03.910
A Second Chance for Vets.

01:35:03.910 --> 01:35:05.480
There's a lot of information
about how to start a court

01:35:05.480 --> 01:35:07.690
or the right questions
to ask your jurisdiction.

01:35:07.690 --> 01:35:09.920
Um, but also you can
contact Justice for Vets.

01:35:09.920 --> 01:35:11.560
They have four mentor courts.

01:35:11.560 --> 01:35:14.070
You can make a request to
actually take a team onsite

01:35:14.070 --> 01:35:18.080
and go see what's going on
and -- and view that court.

01:35:18.080 --> 01:35:19.380
&gt;&gt; Melissa Fitzgerald: Yeah.

01:35:19.380 --> 01:35:20.690
If you're a jurisdiction and you're
interested in any way setting

01:35:20.690 --> 01:35:23.630
up a veteran's treatment court,
please go to our website.

01:35:23.630 --> 01:35:27.790
There's a tremendous amount of
information at JusticeforVets.org.

01:35:27.790 --> 01:35:29.090
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
Let me -- hold on.

01:35:29.090 --> 01:35:30.390
Let me do this real quick.

01:35:30.390 --> 01:35:34.210
Tim, when you came back -- the goal
with PTSD is first diagnosis it,

01:35:34.210 --> 01:35:37.020 position:56%
figuring out what you're up against,
and then intervening as quickly

01:35:37.020 --> 01:35:39.710
as possible so that you can
intercept that from turning

01:35:39.710 --> 01:35:43.840
into really bad decisions and
ultimately trying to determine

01:35:43.840 --> 01:35:45.910
if somebody's going to
go out there and act out,

01:35:45.910 --> 01:35:47.780
which could be committing crimes.

01:35:47.780 --> 01:35:49.160
What would have been in one thing

01:35:49.160 --> 01:35:52.300
that could have intercepted you
immediately coming back from combat

01:35:52.300 --> 01:35:54.940
that would have helped immensely?

01:35:54.940 --> 01:35:56.240
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: A veteran's court.

01:35:56.240 --> 01:35:57.540
No doubt.

01:35:57.540 --> 01:35:58.840
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias:
A veteran's court?

01:35:58.840 --> 01:36:00.140
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: No
doubt in my mind.

01:36:00.140 --> 01:36:01.440
If I were to land in veteran's
court with my first arrest,

01:36:01.440 --> 01:36:02.740
I wouldn't have had seven arrests,

01:36:02.740 --> 01:36:04.210
I wouldn't have spent a
year of my life in prison.

01:36:04.210 --> 01:36:05.960
I wouldn't have not be
in my daughter's life

01:36:05.960 --> 01:36:07.260
for the first four
years of her life.

01:36:07.260 --> 01:36:09.550
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: You needed
a vet to look you in the eye

01:36:09.550 --> 01:36:11.870
and tell you you're a changed man
and you need to get over that,

01:36:11.870 --> 01:36:13.170
you need to figure this out?

01:36:13.170 --> 01:36:14.470
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Absolutely.

01:36:14.470 --> 01:36:15.770
And I need a room where
I can walk into

01:36:15.770 --> 01:36:17.600
and all the resources
are right there.

01:36:17.600 --> 01:36:21.500
A lot of people are perplexed at
veteran's courts, you know, work.

01:36:21.500 --> 01:36:23.520
They say, you know, "How
is this even possible

01:36:23.520 --> 01:36:25.360 position:56%
and doesn't it cost a ton of money?"

01:36:25.360 --> 01:36:27.240
And in reality it's one day a week.

01:36:27.240 --> 01:36:28.900
It's one judge.

01:36:28.900 --> 01:36:30.310
It's one courtroom.

01:36:30.310 --> 01:36:35.450 position:56%
It's one staff for one day per week,
but the impact is unbelievable.

01:36:35.450 --> 01:36:37.000
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: And
they're speaking your language?

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:38.300
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: They're
speaking my language.

01:36:38.300 --> 01:36:39.890
I walk into that room,
I can get everything

01:36:39.890 --> 01:36:41.850
that I need all in one room.

01:36:41.850 --> 01:36:44.790
And that's something that
you can't get anywhere else.

01:36:44.790 --> 01:36:47.580
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: There's
something even before all that.

01:36:47.580 --> 01:36:53.030
If somebody commits a
crime, the first people

01:36:53.030 --> 01:36:55.370
in the criminal justice
system that they're going

01:36:55.370 --> 01:36:59.020
to come across are the police.

01:36:59.020 --> 01:37:03.110
On the Justice Involved Veterans
Network, there's one gentleman,

01:37:03.110 --> 01:37:06.510
Captain Blair Myhand of
Apex, North Carolina.

01:37:06.510 --> 01:37:07.810
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Now Chief.

01:37:07.810 --> 01:37:09.110
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: Now -- OK.

01:37:09.110 --> 01:37:10.410
That I didn't know.

01:37:10.410 --> 01:37:15.310
And what he does is he takes
a couple of vets who are

01:37:15.310 --> 01:37:22.920
on the police force and trains
them in how to deal with a crisis

01:37:22.920 --> 01:37:24.790
if somebody is a veteran.

01:37:24.790 --> 01:37:29.680
And if they know the person's a
veteran because the spouse tells,

01:37:29.680 --> 01:37:35.530
uh, the first officers, these guys
come and they know what to say,

01:37:35.530 --> 01:37:40.970 position:56%
they know how to bring somebody down
from the crisis she's in or he's in.

01:37:40.970 --> 01:37:46.160 position:56%
He also does this training for other
police departments I think twice

01:37:46.160 --> 01:37:47.460
a year.

01:37:47.460 --> 01:37:52.350
But the police have a greater
role that they can play

01:37:52.350 --> 01:37:56.950
and it's not going on as -- nearly
as much as I think it ought to.

01:37:56.950 --> 01:37:58.740
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Is it fair
to say that a barrier right now

01:37:58.740 --> 01:38:01.230
that exists is -- especially
with law enforcement,

01:38:01.230 --> 01:38:03.810
because I know a lot of my
friends who are police officers

01:38:03.810 --> 01:38:06.190
and they tend to give the benefit
of the doubt to a returning vet

01:38:06.190 --> 01:38:07.490
if they're caught up in something.

01:38:07.490 --> 01:38:09.140
They kind of will pat
them on the back and go,

01:38:09.140 --> 01:38:10.640
"Come on, man, don't do this."

01:38:10.640 --> 01:38:14.650
Is that doing them a favor
or is that hurting them?

01:38:14.650 --> 01:38:16.290
Because you're basically in denial.

01:38:16.290 --> 01:38:17.590
You're just saying, "You're a vet,

01:38:17.590 --> 01:38:19.330
I'm going to cut you
some slack here."

01:38:19.330 --> 01:38:20.630
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Yeah.

01:38:20.630 --> 01:38:21.930
It's -- in my opinion, it's
definitely hurting them.

01:38:21.930 --> 01:38:23.230
And I've been cut breaks.

01:38:23.230 --> 01:38:24.530
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: It's
just kicking the can.

01:38:24.530 --> 01:38:25.830
&gt;&gt; Timothy Wynn: Yeah.

01:38:25.830 --> 01:38:27.130
Basically.

01:38:27.130 --> 01:38:28.450
Um, but one of the most
important things at my job now is

01:38:28.450 --> 01:38:31.260
to do crisis intervention training
with the local police department.

01:38:31.260 --> 01:38:33.020
I go up to the Philadelphia
Police Department.

01:38:33.020 --> 01:38:36.100
I go over to Camden, New
Jersey, and I tell my story.

01:38:36.100 --> 01:38:39.460
And I tell them flat out, you
know, the best thing to happen

01:38:39.460 --> 01:38:44.190
to me was getting that final arrest
and not getting let go that day

01:38:44.190 --> 01:38:46.650
and actually getting put
in a veteran's court.

01:38:46.650 --> 01:38:48.330
It absolutely changed my life.

01:38:48.330 --> 01:38:54.640
I educate the police on PTSD, uh,
TBI, you know, domestic violence,

01:38:54.640 --> 01:38:56.650 position:56%
which is very high amongst veterans.

01:38:56.650 --> 01:38:58.670
Um, and I tell my story.

01:38:58.670 --> 01:39:01.930 position:56%
And it really strikes home with
them because, at the end of the day,

01:39:01.930 --> 01:39:04.130
they're the first responders,
they're the ones out on the streets

01:39:04.130 --> 01:39:06.760
that are coming in contact
with these veterans.

01:39:06.760 --> 01:39:10.150
The ones that are out there buying
heroin, getting in bar fights,

01:39:10.150 --> 01:39:12.740
stuff like that, they're the
ones showing up on the scene

01:39:12.740 --> 01:39:14.780
and the decision that they make

01:39:14.780 --> 01:39:19.940
that day could absolutely change
their life, um, for the better.

01:39:19.940 --> 01:39:23.220
Getting arrested is not the worst
thing that can happen to a vet.

01:39:23.220 --> 01:39:24.520
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Go ahead, Greg.

01:39:24.520 --> 01:39:26.050
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: It can be kicking
the can down the road, but it --

01:39:26.050 --> 01:39:27.620
unless you know, you know,
what -- what you're doing.

01:39:27.620 --> 01:39:29.380
You have to understand your
resources in the community

01:39:29.380 --> 01:39:31.120
and you have to be
willing to make a referral.

01:39:31.120 --> 01:39:34.220
Um, I think some of the things
that we're working on at NIC

01:39:34.220 --> 01:39:35.870
and in our partnership
with some of the folks

01:39:35.870 --> 01:39:37.610
up here are a couple things.

01:39:37.610 --> 01:39:41.540
Real quick is increasing what they
call the responsivity issues have

01:39:41.540 --> 01:39:46.640
veterans, looking at developing
training around military culture,

01:39:46.640 --> 01:39:49.440
um, issues transitioning from
military to civilian life,

01:39:49.440 --> 01:39:51.080
the underlying issues
of PTSD, and TBI.

01:39:51.080 --> 01:39:53.240
NIC is working on this curriculum

01:39:53.240 --> 01:39:54.540
with the Center for
Court Innovation.

01:39:54.540 --> 01:39:56.300
We hope to pilot test this in FY-18

01:39:56.300 --> 01:39:57.640
and make this available
to the field.

01:39:57.640 --> 01:40:01.070 position:56%
But in addition to that the National
Institute of Corrections partnered

01:40:01.070 --> 01:40:04.220
with the Bureau of Justice
Assistance, um, and the Center

01:40:04.220 --> 01:40:07.750
for Court Innovation to develop
the first set of screening tools

01:40:07.750 --> 01:40:10.050
that factors in the
complexities of war trauma.

01:40:10.050 --> 01:40:12.740
So there's a comprehensive tool
and a case planning protocol

01:40:12.740 --> 01:40:14.560
that will help guide veterans
treatment courts on how

01:40:14.560 --> 01:40:17.040
to best serve the veterans
in their justice system.

01:40:17.040 --> 01:40:18.340
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: OK.

